album.title: On My Way
album.artist: The Cooper Friendly Feel Good Group
album.description: The Cooper Friendly Feel Good Group's debut album, "On My Way", rendered the band members overwhelming success and fame with songs such as "Thelma Sue" and "Ride in My Truck" soaring to the top of the charts in every country around the globe immediately after it's initial release. The remastered re-released limited collector's edition album only continued the band's reign over the billboard charts and airwaves narrowly annihilating every other artists existence due to the earth's inhabitants lack of interest in any other band's music besides The Cooper Friendly Feel Good Group's. After the near extinction of all other forms of music and under the immense pressure of creating songs to satisfy the audiophilistic cravings of the entire word's population the members of the band kicked off their downward spirals in a big way but, we won't get in to that here. You can catch "The Cooper Friendly Feel Good Group. Behind the Music. The Rise and Fall of The Cooper Friendly Feel Good Group. How They Rose Again." film for more on that part of the story. Now, to sum it up the glorious riches and awesome popularity soon evaporated as the groups hooptie hoo and hollerin' consumed every cent of wealth they had accumulated. Band members squandered it away. Every last bit of it. Rumors have been circulating that the band is working on a new album but that has neither been confirmed nor denied by any of the band's numerous representatives.

album.title: Youth
album.description:
Youth was recorded over the span of an entire year--June 1st, 2013 to approximately June 3rd, 2014. The record is comprised of songs that Temples collectively worked on since March of 2011 when the band unofficially formed.
credits
released September 10, 2014

Youth was written and performed by: Randy Cordner, Nathan Richardson, Chris Andreasen and Timothy Ross.

Youth was engineered, mixed and mastered by Randy Cordner at Beast Mansion Studio between the summers of 2013 and 2014.

Youth was produced by Randy Cordner and Temples.

Additional contributions include: Synths on Lon Lon performed by Tom Perry. Synths on Lost Woods, Sanctus Regnum and Gates of Time performed by Ryon Westover. Vocals on Gates of Time include James F. Barlow and John-Ross Boyce. Upright bass on Village provided by James F. Barlow.

Album artwork and design by Jefferson Smith and Christian Degn Peterson.

Because there are so many amazing, talented and wonderful friends and family members who've helped us along the way, it's difficult to mention everyone here--you know who you are! In particular, however, we'd like to thank: Big Dane and ABG's Libation Emporium, Randy Andreasen, Mike Walton and 90.9 FM KRCL, and, of course, our sister band The Troubles. Thanks to everyone who's purchased a copy of this record or who's ventured to see us play live, we love you!

feeds.title: Heat Lightning
feeds.description:
Long in the making, this follow-up to The Lightningrod Salesman's 'Hiddenkind' album shows the evolution of experimentation and production methods employed by him. From cold, dark house, to warm, penetrating summer shine, to a beautiful night in Atlantic City with electric energy on the air, there's plenty of texture and tune to lose yourself in, and float away on, in this 15 year project. 
Ariel Powell
Bearsnare Records
electronic, dance, experimental, chill, breakbeat, house, electro-chill, psychedelic, ambient, guitar

feeds.title: Midnight Breakheart
feeds.description:
Midnight Breakheart is a six-track EP that took far too long to make. These songs came out kicking, dragging their heels through every version, rewriting, and re-record until they finally landed right where they belonged.
Wired, worn-in, and sharp around the edges.  It’s not perfect, and that’s the point.

You might be twice as big as me, but I've wrestled women that were twice as big as me and I've mopped the floor with them. That's what I'm gonna do with you, Mr. Lawler. album.title: Good Morning
album.description:
Good Morning is an electronic instrumental record that awakens the senses with its vibrant and uplifting soundscapes. From the very first track, the listener is immersed in a world of pulsing rhythms, shimmering synths, and melodic hooks that capture the energy and optimism of a brand new day.

The record's sonic palette is diverse, drawing from a range of electronic sub-genres including ambient, house, techno, and trance. Each track is carefully crafted with meticulous attention to detail, resulting in a cohesive and seamless listening experience that takes the listener on a journey through a kaleidoscope of moods and emotions.

The beats are crisp and driving, providing a solid foundation for the soaring melodies that weave their way through the tracks. At times, the music is contemplative and introspective, with atmospheric pads and intricate arpeggios that evoke a sense of calm and reflection. At other times, the energy ramps up to dizzying heights, with pounding basslines and euphoric chord progressions that inspire movement and celebration.

Whether you're starting your day with a cup of coffee, hitting the gym for a morning workout, or just need a burst of energy to power through your day, Good Morning is the perfect soundtrack for any occasion. Its infectious rhythms and uplifting melodies are sure to put a smile on your face and leave you feeling inspired and motivated.

album.title: Show Me Where They Touched You
album.description:
Volume One of Skatenigs Classics!
Liner Notes:
Chemical imbalance- The first Skatenigs track to be recorded. We recorded live at Trax studio in Chicago under the direction of Al Jourgensen. Lorri Jackson wrote the prologue and performed it the next day. Al worked his magic. Jim and Danny at Wax Trax records loved it and the rest is history.

Shit Authority- This was the first track the band had ever written. It started with a 2 Live Crew beat, a punk riff and a general disdain for authority.

Horny for Evil- Al and I had joked around during Beers, Steers and Queers session about writing a song about how many lives are murdered with each ejaculation and there you have it. The phone call intro was Phildo calling from studio B to studio A at Trax studio. Critter took the call and recorded it. By the way, stupid people really shouldn’t breed.

Passion for Destruction- One of the first songs written for the sophomore release What a Mangled Web We Leave. Inspired by the band mascot, a pit bull named Grunt, amongst many reasons why we can’t have nice things.

Texas Tattoo- Possibly the origin for the idea to build a wall on the Texas border except our concept was to build it on the north border between Oklahoma and our great country.

Hoosegow- Lets just say jail is never a great place to be but even worse if that jail is in Mexico. Can’t say I remember a whole lot from my trips to see Dr Lopez and the family pharmacy in Nuevo Laredo but I can say the statute of limitations is my friend.

Car Crash- We we’re trying to create a song that was fast and furious without it just being another thrash track. Mark Dufour masterfully cut the riff and the beat up to give this song it’s mechanical splendor. The rest relied on speed and a lot of it! *Al really wanted this track for a Revolting Cocks song but I made the choice to keep it for the album Adult Entertainment for Kids.

Stick it In- Everyone loves the Cramps and so do I. This was our take on rockabilly or hellbilly or whatever. We still enjoy playing this one and I hope we do another one soon.

Wake up- If there is ever such a thing as goth rap I want credit for it. This song explores the doom and gloom of the world we have created for ourselves. The bass line I wrote on a mini moog at the original Musiclab in Austin. 
credits
released August 28, 2020

All tracks written and produced by Skatenigs except those that are credited to Al Jourgensen.
album.summary:
Volume One of Skatenigs Classics!
Liner Notes:
Chemical imbalance- The first Skatenigs track to be recorded. We recorded live at Trax studio in Chicago under the direction of Al Jourgensen. Lorri Jackson wrote the prologue and performed it the next day. Al worked his magic. Jim and Danny at Wax Trax records loved it and the rest is history.

Shit Authority- This was the first track the band had ever written. It started with a 2 Live Crew beat, a punk riff and a general disdain for authority.

Horny for Evil- Al and I had joked around during Beers, Steers and Queers session about writing a song about how many lives are murdered with each ejaculation and there you have it. The phone call intro was Phildo calling from studio B to studio A at Trax studio. Critter took the call and recorded it. By the way, stupid people really shouldn’t breed.

Passion for Destruction- One of the first songs written for the sophomore release What a Mangled Web We Leave. Inspired by the band mascot, a pit bull named Grunt, amongst many reasons why we can’t have nice things.

Texas Tattoo- Possibly the origin for the idea to build a wall on the Texas border except our concept was to build it on the north border between Oklahoma and our great country.

Hoosegow- Lets just say jail is never a great place to be but even worse if that jail is in Mexico. Can’t say I remember a whole lot from my trips to see Dr Lopez and the family pharmacy in Nuevo Laredo but I can say the statute of limitations is my friend.

Car Crash- We we’re trying to create a song that was fast and furious without it just being another thrash track. Mark Dufour masterfully cut the riff and the beat up to give this song it’s mechanical splendor. Stick it In- Everyone loves the Cramps and so do I. This was our take on rockabilly or hellbilly or whatever. We still enjoy playing this one and I hope we do another one soon.

Wake up- If there is ever such a thing as goth rap I want credit for it. This song explores the doom and gloom of the world we have created for ourselves. The bass line I wrote on a mini moog at the original Musiclab in Austin.

tracks.title: METAL IN THE BANJO
tracks.subtitle: METAL IN THE BANJO
tracks.summary:
METAL IN THE BANJO by TJ Doerfel(Sir TJ The Wrathful)
I made this song for Sir Libre after somehow it came up in discussion that I should make a metal banjo song. It took on it's own sound, not exactly metal, but close enough. However, after over 25 hours of creating and producing it, my Macbook with all the projects files, it's hard drive died. I was unable to recover the project or anything else on it and after trying to remove the HD, smashed it with a hammer with wrath. I had saved a few semi-mixed versions, and decided to move forward and release it. 
Fun fact: 5 string banjos are surprisingly heavy, coming in at around 12 pounds. It's because other than the neck, it has a lot of metal pecies that help make up its tone.

album.title: Fell Through the Cracks, Misfits and Rejects: 20 Years of BearSnare Records
album.description:
This album is a Music Side Project exclusive! It can only be heard on podcasting 2.0 platforms. Boost Away!

Over the years, I have produced so much music that some of it inevitably drifts down, between the cracks in the floorboards. Some of the songs are actually quite strong, but just didn't properly fit on an album. Others are goofy, profane, or messy. Even this compilation is not comprehensive, and there still exist more unreleased tracks and albums from BearSnare Records. This is, however, a decent sampling of my various projects over the years. Friends join me on a number of these, and there's one song that I may not have played on at all, but recorded and "produced".
You'll find everything from pop-rock and alternative to dance, grunge, chill electro, and just some good old jams and home recordings here.
Thanks for listening.

-BearSnare

tracks.title: Noisediver - Toothache
tracks.summary:
1. Noisediver – Toothache

We played and recorded a number of versions of this song. It was a fun jam that we’d play whenever we hung out after work. My part was written about a bad coworker. My buddy wrote his part, and it worked. Energetic, heavy, and aggressive, with some melody to balance it out.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell - PriVate Sector
tracks.summary:
2. Ariel Powell – PriVate Sector

Another aggressive tune, from probably ‘08 or so. This one’s a political rant!

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – Floodplains and Dr. Paul
tracks.summary:
3. Ariel Powell – Floodplains and Dr. Paul

Here’s the first song I recorded after moving into a bungalow on stilts by the river. It was a beautiful setting in which to play music.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell - Repugnant As I Try
tracks.summary:
4. Ariel Powell - Repugnant As I Try

This repugnant little tune was inspired by a girl who liked me. I liked her at first, until I realized that all she ever did was complain.

tracks.title: Ariel and Casey – Haunted
tracks.summary:
5. Ariel and Casey – Haunted

I once dragged a coworker home to the loft studio at my parents. He rocked at guitar! We figured out a way to play to some lyrics that i had laying around, which had come to me from someone in prison who I didn’t know, through a mutual. This is not at all what he had envisioned for his song, but oh well, haha, we had fun!

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – Trainwreck Waiting
tracks.summary:
6. Ariel Powell – Trainwreck Waiting

An ex wrote the chorus for this song, and I had fun making it. I somehow found a cool vocal harmony here. It’s cheesy and dumb, but whatever, YOLO!

tracks.title: The Lightningrod Salesman – Dawg Fighting
tracks.summary:
7. The Lightningrod Salesman – Dawg Fighting

Remember Michael Vick, the NFL player, and the dog fighting scandal? WELL, let me tell you!
U.S. Senator Robert Byrd, the KKK grand wizard or whatever, was getting kinda old at the time, and made a wonderful, epic botch of his speech regarding this issue. He had many papers, with HUGE print, and there was much shuffling of them.
I’m pretty sure he didn’t care this much when it was humans whom he voted to torture and kill, so I feel ok laughing at him through this fun track. I did surprisingly little editing to his speech, this is pretty much how it was delivered.

tracks.title: The Lightningrod Salesman – Shake Me
tracks.summary:
8. The Lightningrod Salesman – Shake Me

Get into your headphones, so you can hear the dice tumbling and the paint can spraying. This one’s an immersive experience.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – This Perfect Day
tracks.summary:
9. Ariel Powell – This Perfect Day

Ah, young romance! ‘05-’06-ish. Like some of the other older songs on this collection, this was recorded on a 16 track recorder. It was digital, but worked like a multitrack tape recorder. This process of recording was very different than the new, computerized, visual way. Something about the sounds I found on this song reminds me of how good my old 16 track could sound.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – After the Waves Break
tracks.summary:
10. Ariel Powell – After the Waves Break

Well dang it, it’s another young romance song. This one’s a bit more distant and desperate. Also ‘05-’06.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – They Cover You in Snow
tracks.summary:
11. Ariel Powell – They Cover You in Snow

An immersive and passionate jam with myself. I don’t remember what inspired this, but I was feeling it.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell - Garden Calendar
tracks.summary:
12. Ariel Powell - Garden Calendar

Some things start as a soundtrack to a video or slideshow, and that’s what this was. It turned out nicely enough that I’ll call it a song! It could almost go under the lightningrod salesman name, due to the electric drums. But it’s nice chill guitar, and very post-rock. So I’m claiming it!

tracks.title: The Lightningrod Salesman – APAX
tracks.summary:
13. The Lightningrod Salesman – APAX

Here’s a weird thing that I recorded in my brother’s basement when we lived there, in between houses. I had just been gifted a saxophone, which I am still very rough at. This number has a weird, something’s wrong kind of vibe.

tracks.title: The Lightningrod Salesman - Oh, How the Spring Doth Weep!
tracks.summary:
14. The Lightningrod Salesman - Oh, How the Spring Doth Weep!

This started as a cover song, see if you can figure out which one. I think it turned out quite distinct from it’s inspiration. I might still go back and add real drums to this. The piano is nice and evocative.

tracks.title: The Lightningrod Salesman – EOL Intro
tracks.summary:
15. The Lightningrod Salesman – EOL Intro

Originally intended as an intro to ‘Empire of Lies’, I decided that it didn’t fit, and I was bothered by putting the good Dr. Paul’s voice into this hellscape of sound. But it’s a cool little piece, and Dr. Paul’s voice echoes through with the harsh truth.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – Whispers and Prayers
tracks.summary:
16. Ariel Powell – Whispers and Prayers

From the original version of ‘The Leaves, Shimmering Gold’, this is yet again another misfit that I rejected from the newer versions of that album released online today. It’s really more appropriate under ‘the lightningrod salesman’ moniker, but this song was born first.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – Only With Each-Other
tracks.summary:
17. Ariel Powell – Only With Each-Other

This is an alternate version of the last song on “Empire of Lies”, “Snow Jar”. I went back and forth trying to decide which version to release with the album, since I had both in-hand. This one is kinda tighter, but the other version was the original, and I really liked my brother Toby’s vocals on it.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell - Another Lost Day
tracks.summary:
18. Ariel Powell - Another Lost Day

Man, I’m glad I’ve found my Keeper since this pathetic little indulgence.
Haha it’s kinda cool anyway. There’s an epic and expansive aspect to whatever this is. Rough vocals, I know. The masters are lost to time, but cool jam, I hope.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – Mother, I’m Alive!
tracks.summary:
19. Ariel Powell – Mother, I’m Alive!

The oldest song in this collection, circa 2001.
I was a senior in high school when a very close friend in the dorm died. He was besties with my brother, and well loved by everyone in the school. He had a wild, flamboyant, theatrical and dtramatic personality. He was a cripple, with something similar to cerebral palsy. He was literally a hunchback, but he played the hammer dulcimer beautifully, hiked multiple mountains despite being crippled (a true example of willpower), and he knew how to laugh. This song’s for Justin.

tracks.title: Dudes 4 Deep – I Used to Be Happy
tracks.summary:
20. Dudes 4 Deep – I Used to Be Happy

The first ever Dudes 4 Deep song. In the loft, at my parents, in our early 20’s, not sober.
Something magical happened here, half of us really didn’t play instruments. But somehow we made a weird thing happen, and therefore went on to make even weirder things happen on subsequent days and evenings of not-soberness.

tracks.title: Dudes 4 Deep - Bottle and Drum
tracks.summary:
Dudes 4 Deep - Bottle and Drum

Dudes (and dudettes) late at night, inebriated, making noise! Great call and response here.

tracks.title: Dudes 4 Deep – Ruminations on Bourbon
tracks.summary:
21. Dudes 4 Deep – Ruminations on Bourbon

Oh boy, here we go, it’s getting late, we just got back from the bar, and BearSnare’s hitting record. Time to hop on some instruments and wax eloquent about the wonders of bourbon and each-other.
I’ll spare the names of my co-conspirators on this drunken endeavor, because I’m quite sure that’s how they want it.

tracks.title: Dudes 4 Deep – Haulin’ Loads
tracks.summary:
22. Dudes 4 Deep – Haulin’ Loads

Truckers got it rough. Late night, early morning, who can even tell the difference?
I don’t think this dude ever drove truck for a living, but other dudes certainly do.

tracks.title: Noisediver – Chimney Tops
tracks.summary:
23. Noisediver – Chimney Tops

Sleepy and very homegrown, but somehow hypnotizing. Thanks for the good times, Chief.

tracks.title: Ariel Powell – Hunnybutt
tracks.summary:
24. Ariel Powell – Hunnybutt

I make a valentine’s mix for my wife every year. I did this as a bonus track ; *

album.summary:
This album is a Music Side Project exclusive! It can only be heard on podcasting 2.0 platforms. Boost Away!

Over the years, I have produced so much music that some of it inevitably drifts down, between the cracks in the floorboards. Some of the songs are actually quite strong, but just didn't properly fit on an album. Others are goofy, profane, or messy. Even this compilation is not comprehensive, and there still exist more unreleased tracks and albums from BearSnare Records. This is, however, a decent sampling of my various projects over the years. Friends join me on a number of these, and there's one song that I may not have played on at all, but recorded and "produced".
You'll find everything from pop-rock and alternative to dance, grunge, chill electro, and just some good old jams and home recordings here.
Thanks for listening.

-BearSnare

feeds.title: The Attic and the River
feeds.description:
Over the space of about a decade, three or four good friends would get together after work or on the weekend, and play music together.
Sometimes it was just jamming, and sometimes it was a more methodical production. Either way, Ariel always tried to hit record, and sometimes something beautiful happened.
The attic and the river are representative of the two different music studios used in the making of this music. One was in the attic of Ariel's parents' garage, and the other was at his bungalow on stilts down by the river.
  
released March 20, 2022
Ariel Powell- production, drums, vocals...

album.title: What Could Go Wrong?
album.description:
AUSTIN, TX. - Skatenigs, the long-running electro-thrashcore outfit led by singer Phil "Phildo" Owen, return to the musical stage with What Could Go Wrong?, a collection of all-new recordings, on Armalyte Industries on October 29.

Featuring the current core Skatenigs crew of Owen, Chris Ahrens and Adam Lamar on guitars, and live drummer/studio bassist Myke Bingham (Owen: "He's a one-man rhythm section!"), the 12-track physical CD release will be followed by its digital streaming counterpart via Cleopatra Records on Halloween.

Skatenigs was begun by Owen in Los Angeles in 1989, though it's been Austin-based since the early '90s. Running until 1995, with a brief reunion for a handful of shows in 2011, Skatenigs were reactivated in 2016 for their self-released Adult Entertainment For Kids, with all current members augmented by Big Boys/Poison 13/Junkyard legend Chris Gates. What Could Go Wrong? basically comprises what Skatenigs did during COVID-19 lockdown.

All 12 tracks were written and recorded in fits and starts, between dayjob engagements and other responsibilities. Among the highlights: A steroid-enhanced, turbo-charged, 30th anniversary "Life, Liberty and the Pursuit Of Happiness" remake/remix of "Beers, Steers and Queers," the Revolting Cocks hit featuring Owen's vocals. The new version of "BSAQ" is essentially the original version, with new guitar work and other instrumental contributions from Skatenigs, plus some choice samples from Joe Exotic. "It's gonna get real redneck," promises Owen.

The core Skatenigs quartet is augmented by a who's-who of punk/hardcore/metal/industrial heroes. Among the luminaries, besides Gates:

Dan Milligan- Joy Thieves
Andy Selway- Dwarves, KMFDM
Jason West- Wednesday 13, Creed Fisher Riggs- Rob Zombie, Scum of the Earth Spit Stix- Fear
Pablo Flores- Worm Suicide Galen Waling- Pig/Lords of Acid Charles Levi- Thrill Kill Kult Bradley Bills- Chant
Mike Deleon- Philip H Anselmo and the Illegals David Skar Carpenter- Circle Burn/Snow Black Cesar Soto- Ministry
Greg Hetson- Circle Jerks, Bad Religion

Seemed like a good idea at the time(Ahrens,Gates,Owen)

Burn this motherfucker to the god damned ground(Carpenter,Owen)

Beers Steers and Queers- Life Liberty and the Pursuit of Happiness Mix (Owen,Jourgensen,Van Acker,Rieflin,Barker,Connelly)

feeds.title: Get Away
feeds.description:
The Velvick's third single off their debut album "Greatest Hits" under Cannabis Records. Come with us through a journey of fast love and lust. Sometimes it burns so fast and bright when you're swept away by the moment. But is it real love or just a smoldering passion? What happens when the match burns down to your fingers? Did you trick yourself to romance? Hope you learned your lesson then. Reach out to your old friends and start a rock and roll band. Get away!
(P)(C) Cannabis Records
Presented by Cannabis Records and Hash Power Music

album.title: Good Clean Fun... My Ass
album.description:
Punk rock may be a traditionally tricky intersection for art and commerce, but former Skatenig Phil Owen has chosen his side. "Everything is for sale," says Owen. In fact, one could say this statement of purpose is at the heart of Choreboy, Owen's retro-punk side-project he founded alongside former Big Boy Chris Gates and fellow Skatenig alumnus Mat Mitchell. Fittingly, then, "We're in It for the Money" is Choreboy's anthem, as well as the lead-off track from the group's debut, Good Clean Fun… My Ass, a punchy little album from a project Owen says takes its name from a scrubbing pad junkies use as a crack pipe filter, and is ultimately little more than an outlet for "three angry bald guys singing about skinheads."

https://www.last.fm/music/Choreboy/+wiki

feeds.title: The Helicopter View
feeds.description:
This doomy little ditty comes from a long afternoon of jamming with Glen. It was our first time playing together during the plandemic, and we recorded for hours. 
Then, more recently, a friend asked me to come up with an intro for his new podcast. He asked for something doom metal, ending with a sting. So I started going through some stuff I had sitting around, and I managed to dredge this out and add some vocals, bass, and more guitars.

feeds.title: I'm Hungry
feeds.description:
Songs written with food in mind! 
For his 12th album, Bratcher gathered several musical friends in Kansas City and Nashville to record 10 original tracks and two inspired cover songs to round out this unique project.
The music ranges from barrelhouse boogie to straight-ahead blues, roots rock, and soul, mixed to enhance and inspire the downhome recipes, creating an entertaining and irreverent collection.

album.title: I'm Hungry
album.description:
Songs written with food in mind! 

For his 12th album, Bratcher gathered several musical friends in Kansas City and Nashville to record 10 original tracks and two inspired cover songs to round out this unique project.

The music ranges from barrelhouse boogie to straight-ahead blues, roots rock, and soul, mixed to enhance and inspire the downhome recipes, creating an entertaining and irreverent collection.

tracks.title: Greasy (Instrumental)
tracks.summary: From Jimmie’s collection of food songs, Greasy is just what the chef ordered, with enough greasy goodness and flavor for everyone.

tracks.title: Green Bananas
tracks.summary: When a 98-year-old goes shopping for bananas, you know there’s a story about to happen.

tracks.title: Bacon Is On My Mind
tracks.summary: With the song, ‘Bacon Is On My Mind,’ Bratcher uses a bump and grind 12-bar blues to pontificate about one of the world’s most powerful olfactory senses. The gritty guitars and intense piano will take you to a blues wonderland!

tracks.title: Mama Won't Fry No Chicken
tracks.summary: This song is for everyone who has been told, “You’ve got to cut out the cheese and fried foods.” Then your wife tells you no more fried chicken. That is what you call the blues. From Jimmie’s 2021 album, “I’m Hungry.” I’m Hungry is a collection of songs all about food, with a companion 260-page family cookbook.

album.title: Man! It's Christmas
album.description:
A collection of some of Jimmie's favorite Christmas songs and a few originals.

Man! It's Christmas hits the ground running with a jubilant classic jazz rendition of the Bratcher-penned title track "Man! It's Christmas", which expresses the joy of the season while referencing just about every holiday symbol there is. A smokin’ jazz-funk version of “What Child Is This” follows, and it leads you into a down-home dobro-driven country blues arrangement of “Go Tell It On The Mountain.” Patriotic Christmas song “1941,” another original Bratcher tune, recalls the WWII events of December 1941. It expresses appreciation for those who have served our country and laid down their lives for our freedom. Backing Bratcher on the project are some world-class players, including Rick York (Suzy Bogguss, Lee Roy Parnell) on bass, Daron Tapscott (Joe Diffie) on fiddle, Kansas City’s Brandon Draper on drums and percussion, and Eric Stark on keys and trumpet.

tracks.summary: A patriotic Christmas song, “1941,” recalls the WWII events of December 1941. It expresses appreciation for those who have served our country and laid down their lives for our freedom—dedicated to Jimmie’s parents, Pete & Marge.

I used to walk down Christmastree Lane
To see the lights shining and Santa ride in his sleigh
Now there's a cloud that comes every year
He doesn't know how to show holiday cheer

My man hates Christmas
More than anyone I know
Can't stand the stockings
Avoids the mistletoe
My man hates Christmas
We haven't got a tree

This year for me

feeds.title: Bryan's Christmas
feeds.description: Bryan Duncan's favorite Christmas songs.

album.title: Bryan's Christmas
album.description: Bryan Duncan's favorite Christmas songs.

tracks.title: I Heard The Bells
tracks.summary: My first feelings at Christmas. I need to be reminded of where to place my focus.

tracks.title: The Form Of Man
tracks.summary: The Form Of Man - The story of Jesus' birth in layman’s terms and his astonishing purpose for coming.

tracks.title: This Christmas
tracks.summary: I wrote this one year at a Christmas banquet that went long. I ran out of songs I knew how to play, so I wrote it backstage on break. It’s mostly about the ‘aftermath’ and the one gift that keeps on giving.

tracks.title: Angels We Have Heard On High
tracks.summary: I had to dress this one up for my own taste, it was a standard at every Christmas Eve church service that I remember. Meant to be sung by a cast of 'little angels' in that Christmas pageant.

tracks.title: Christmas Card
tracks.summary: My own composition. Written about a transcendent moment with one of my kids. Whose words mean more than gifts could ever bring. That card is framed and sitting in my office two decades later.

tracks.title: Hark The Herald Angels Sing
tracks.summary: This was a staple in our Christmas caroling back when it wasn’t dangerous to go door to door singing songs of Joy and Peace throughout the world.

tracks.title: Silent Night
tracks.summary: How could I not record the most recorded song of all time at Christmas? But then nothing speaks to tranquility and peace of soul like this song. Here I ‘fancied it up’ for the sake of the project. But the truth is, it’s best song without music at all.

tracks.title: O Holy Night
tracks.summary: I heard Miles Davis do this on trumpet, a reverently sophisticated presentation of the most world changing event ever. I have no idea of his personal convictions about faith in Jesus. But to tell the story of the beginning of salvation in a jazz format has its own conviction.

tracks.title: Away In A Manger/O Come to My Heart
tracks.summary: Ever wonder what a Heavenly Host might sound like singing? This is the biggest production piece I’ve ever recorded. Using a one hundred voice choir and a live orchestra, it’s movie soundtrack quality but a little hard to pull off on tour on a humble man’s budget.

tracks.title: The First Noel
tracks.summary: This song has a lonely feel to it. Perfect for the lack of fanfare that came with the birth of Christ. Just another day to those who were living unaware.

tracks.title: Christmas Is Jesus
tracks.summary: Another of my own compositions, this song came out of my annoyance that many were turning “Merry Christmas” into the generic "Happy Holidays”.  Allow me to be dogmatic.

tracks.title: Christmas Comes But Once A Year

feeds.title: All That's Haunting Me
feeds.description:
My early to mid-twenties were full of romantic drama, self-discovery, musical passion, depression, and directionless wandering, searching for my place in the world. This music largely represents some nasty breakups and my loneliness and insecurities. Despite all the anger and discouragement on display here, there are also moments of brightness, beauty, and hope. 
My musical influences here include deftones, sigur-ros, brand new, thursday, circa survive, matthew goodband, and many, many, more.
Grunge, alternative, rock, prog-rock,

tracks.title: Babble Bright
tracks.summary:
Try to remember
Where you came from
Look for a clue
To the reason you’re here
The end of the road
Is not far away
Will you be here
At the end of the road
At the end of the road
And if not then why
If not then don’t stay around
Just let the words slip away from you
Just let the reasons come back to you
It’s red and blue lights
The entire show
And you can’t really run
When you are surrounded

tracks.title: Back into the Ashes
tracks.summary:
And so we are the last ones
Once again to leave
The fire still blinds you
And once again you’re full speed ahead
With your heart on the line
Am I here to think about
Am I here to make amends
Well I am not here to tell you what to do
What if it just wasn’t murder
Though you swear that it was them
Am I just dreaming
Would you lock me away
Would I be the sinner who broke your power
Who let everyone know the truth about you
And so we are the last ones
Once again to leave
Is the light from her eyes
Too bright for you to see
So now the night finds you
Taken to the ground
You’re nothing you’re everything to me
And the fire still blinds you at full speed ahead
You awake for an instant
Then go back into the ashes 
Where first you chose loneliness

tracks.title: Black Shyed
tracks.summary:
Blame it on her highness
Who imagines she is king
Blame it on the emperor
Who thinks that he is king
Let there be no other
Holier than this
Thing that we cherish
And crave like the wind
And the sea
So save me from the rocks on the shore
Of the sea and save me from
Her highness who protects me from the truth

tracks.title: Proud
tracks.summary:
There is a point at which we break
Every one of us
And everything inside you disappears
And still you’re here
You must go on
To make me proud
Make your parents glad you’re theirs
And once again
It all explodes
And  you are left with nothing but your shame
To make you get up
And join the fight again
Join the fight again
Join the fight again
Join the fight again

tracks.title: Cry for the Innocence
tracks.summary:
The end of the earth is apparent to me
The end of the earth is inside me
Where nothing is sure and purity is slain
The end of the earth seems alright to me
Cry for the innocence
That left you far behind
Cry for the love that gets harder to find
With every kiss of jealousy
With every broken heart
And it’s try try try
And you’re always falling down
Harder and harder with each passing year
And further away from the warmth of her arms
One day long ago
You could cry
Now all of those tears won’t ever see light
And all of your dreams are locked up inside
No one left who can let it all out
Nowhere left to be alone
And scream your cares away
No one left to just
If not for the first time 
Maybe the last time
Would never have been such a failure

tracks.title: All that's Haunting Me
tracks.summary:
This time you will find me outside
Sailing through the night
Don’t look for me if you’re scared
Of all that’s haunting me
Don’t look at me like I’m just another guy
Who once to wanted to fuck
All her razors leave a mark
All her actions out for everyone to see
All her actions in the light
Shame, shame, shame makes you run away
It’s plain, plain, plain
That guilty look upon your heart
Don’t blame me for the pain that you dealt
Tell all your friends I am not your lover
Tell all your friends I am not your man
All her razors leave a mark
All her actions out for everyone to see
All you say sinks deeper into me now
All your vows are inseparable
From here we can only grow further apart
How can I go on to find another love
All her razors leave a mark
All her actions out for everyone to see
Tell your friends I am not your lover
Tell your friends I am not your man anymore
And gravity betrays me
Every night it’s on my chest
Every night when I’m still wanting you
Just a word would you drop me
Just a word a guilty sword
To help me soon forget
Your razor marks

tracks.title: Give Me More Noise
tracks.summary:
Every Saturday morning
We’ll drink coffee till our kidneys explode
We’ll make sense and believe it
We’ll laugh until we all collide
But I just want noise
Turn up the gain and blow all our ears out 
Till justice prevails
And the greedy attorney gets his veal tonight
Give me more noise
It’s craving and pacing and muttering sour
Or give me her voice
Or it will stop
Take your breath away
You won’t remember which way you were going
I want to shine
Like the stars in her eyes
I want to let go 
Of the secrets I hide
Just please please please smile

tracks.title: Q of H
tracks.summary:
What the fuck was I thinking
Not telling you I love you
We both know it’s the truth
But I just cannot recite it
Now play dead I’m the peregrine
I’ll make my presence known
Now play castle queen of hearts
The kingdom at your door
Now what the fuck was I thinking
I went and called you again
Do you want to hang out and play hooky
But you won’t return my call
Keep playing dead to me I am the fool
Who cannot let go of his dream
High in your castle you’re shimmering white
As the fool falls dead at the door

tracks.title: Stay Away
tracks.summary:
You were away
I should have known your apathy
Naivety ends in lonesome drugs and left over pain
Anything to suffocate
The irresponsibility your whoring proclaims in you
You were away
So I sent you roses and a song
You had me blind
In darkness and in bliss
Thank you for the graciousness with which you lower me
I’ll be happy and alone
This is my promise to you 
Now you have to promise me
You’ll stay away
I’ll be happy and alone

tracks.title: Dirty
tracks.summary:
You’re always tired
It’s not a good sign
Girls always sleep when they want to break up
I’m always quiet
It’s not a good sign
Boys get withdrawn when they want something dirty
We’re always drunk and
Nothing’s your fault when
The room’s spinning round and you’re just having fun
You think that I am
Just another guy
Looking for action and I’ve proved you right
Well I wonder which is going to happen first
Will I clean up or will she come along
The girl that I want is dirty
But she makes me clean
Yeah she’s a little dirty
But that angry stare that stabs right through my memory
It makes me feel like her dirty

tracks.title: Coming Clean
tracks.summary:
Last night I came clean
Clean to you after so long
Years have gone by now
I thought you knew
When I sang brown eyed girl to you
Woah woah woah

We promise with kisses

A love of a lifetime

tracks.summary:
You breathe the sky
A warm breeze blows
You break some hearts
But you have many more
The stars and the moon
Are what you’re looking for
So pull one down tonight
Leaves shine like gold

Without all the cares
Because it’s raining today

To just stay inside and sleep it away
And dream of the clever things you’ll say

This candle shows the way
Through doorways hidden from the sun
Her footsteps echo through
Corridors dressed in marble
Diamonds in the moonlight
Do you love
The time when It’s spring

album.summary:
My early to mid-twenties were full of romantic drama, self-discovery, musical passion, depression, and directionless wandering, searching for my place in the world. This music largely represents some nasty breakups and my loneliness and insecurities. Despite all the anger and discouragement on display here, there are also moments of brightness, beauty, and hope. 

My musical influences here include deftones, sigur-ros, brand new, thursday, circa survive, matthew goodband, and many, many, more.

tracks.title: Apathy
tracks.summary:
Apathy and empathy go toe-to-toe
The secrets of the universe I long to know
What’s it for? If it’s not all for show?
Biding your time for the final blow
One moment I’m freezing, the next, I’m soaking wet
A sickening obsession, wake from nightmares dripping sweat
My heart will catch up in my chest, familiar story, you know the rest
The silent rage & anger build a hidden volcano erupts at will

I’ll miss the vast open space
And the fresh mountain air
In this stifling situation
With little patience to spare

Summer came & left again, now I’ll watch the colors change
Blowing leaves, soon to be set free, must find the whole thing strange
This impermanence, a graceful dance, that’s stood the test of time
Your beauty and the soul within, a glimpse of the divine
But when the dust settles and we figure all this out
Once our fears cease to meddle, we’ll know what we’re about
I will hold on happily, until I lose the fight
Even the wind will lose the sun, as we drift into the night

I’ll miss the vast open space
And the fresh mountain air
In this stifling situation
With little patience to spare

tracks.title: Baby I Do
tracks.subtitle: Baby I Do
tracks.summary: "Baby I Do" is a heartwarming country ballad that weaves the timeless tale of love, commitment, and the simple joys of life shared with someone special. Set against the backdrop of a serene country landscape, the song captures the essence of a love that is as deep as it is enduring. Through its lilting melodies and poignant lyrics, it tells the story of two souls bound by a promise of forever, a vow whispered under the vast, open skies.

tracks.title: Girl Raised in Texas
tracks.subtitle: Girl Raised in Texas
tracks.summary: "Girl Raised in Texas" is a spirited anthem that celebrates the unique qualities and experiences of a woman brought up in the heart of Texas. With a blend of country rock and a hint of blues, this song weaves a vivid narrative that captures the essence of Texas life.

tracks.title: Baby I'll Be Missing You
tracks.subtitle: Baby I'll Be Missing You
tracks.summary: "Baby I'll Be Missing You" is a poignant country ballad that delves deep into the heartache and complexity of longing for someone who has been unfaithful. Through its soul-stirring lyrics and melancholic melodies, the song captures the inner turmoil of a woman coming to terms with her partner's betrayal, yet finding herself unable to shake off the love and memories they shared.

tracks.title: Line Dance This
tracks.subtitle: Line Dance This
tracks.summary: "Line Dance This" is an upbeat, lively country song that captures the spirit and joy of line dancing, a cherished tradition in country culture. The song invites listeners to hit the dance floor with its catchy rhythms and infectious chorus, making it impossible to stay still. With a blend of classic country instruments and modern flair, it's a track that appeals to both traditional and contemporary country fans.

tracks.title: With All of My Heart
tracks.subtitle: With All of My Heart
tracks.summary: "With All of My Heart" is a tender, soul-stirring country ballad that dives deep into the realms of love, dedication, and heartfelt promises. Through its poignant lyrics and warm, melodic harmonies, the song tells the story of unwavering love and the deep commitment one feels towards their partner, pledging to love them with every beat of their heart.

tracks.title: She's My New Girl Going On
tracks.subtitle: She's My New Girl Going On
tracks.summary: "She's My New Girl Going On" is an upbeat, rollicking country track that captures the exhilarating feeling of falling in love all over again. With its catchy melodies, toe-tapping rhythms, and vibrant instrumentation, this song is a celebration of new beginnings and the joy that comes with finding love when you least expect it.

tracks.title: Letter To Joe
tracks.subtitle: Letter To Joe
tracks.summary: "Letter to Joe" transforms into a unique piece within the country genre as a talk song, where the narrative depth and emotional resonance come through in spoken word, set against a backdrop of country instrumentation. This format allows for a more intimate, conversational style, drawing listeners into a deeply personal story as if they're sitting right there, listening to an old friend recount a tale from days gone by.

tracks.title: No Other Woman
tracks.subtitle: No Other Woman
tracks.summary: "No Other Woman" is an exuberant, toe-tapping country anthem that celebrates love and devotion in the most upbeat and infectious way possible. With its lively melody, catchy hook, and rollicking rhythms, this song is a jubilant declaration of a man's unwavering commitment to the love of his life, asserting that there's simply no other woman for him.

tracks.title: Colorado in The Spring
tracks.subtitle: Colorado in The Spring
tracks.summary: "Colorado in The Spring" is an upbeat, vibrant country song that celebrates the rejuvenating spirit of springtime in one of America's most picturesque landscapes. With a lively tempo, catchy melody, and rich instrumental arrangement, this track is an ode to the beauty, adventure, and sense of renewal that Colorado offers as winter fades and spring takes hold.

tracks.title: The Motor Cross
tracks.subtitle: The Motor Cross
tracks.summary: "The Motor Cross" is a high-energy, upbeat country song that captures the thrill and freedom of motocross racing. With its fast-paced rhythms, catchy guitar riffs, and foot-stomping beats, this track is a celebration of the dirt track, the roar of engines, and the adrenaline rush of competition.

Set against the backdrop of a serene country landscape, the song captures the essence of a love that is as deep as it is enduring. Through its lilting melodies and poignant lyrics, it tells the story of two souls bound by a promise of forever, a vow whispered under the vast, open skies.

feeds.title: ZzA!
feeds.description:
2005 Ariel Powell. At a very pivotal and inspired point in my life, I created each of these songs in one day. I had been playing in a local party/jam band, and I was really feeling the jazzy, dancey, rasta-funky vibe of what we’d been playing. So I took advantage of my week off, and put as much of that into the record as I could. 
Avant-garde and Improv present here, as well as fusion jazz, psychedelic, jam, funk, rock, and blues.

I had been playing in a local party/jam band, and I was really feeling the jazzy, dancey, rasta-funky vibe of what we’d been playing. So I took advantage of my week off, and put as much of that into the record as I could. 

Avant-garde and Improv present here, as well as fusion jazz, psychedelic, jam, funk, rock, and blues.

On this album,the exception on to this track-a-day stint is “Church of the Universe”. It came a few months later, after I had traveled much, and then come home and bought my first computer based recording system. It kinda fits in, despite it’s vastly different recording system. It is the landing after the leap, the shore that welcomed me after a wild, tumultuous journey.

tracks.title: White Spinner Moon
tracks.summary:
The first night I had just finished my last day of work at the factory. I was about to endeavor on a journey out west, in search of a successful music career.  I had a week to get ready for the trip, and on that first night, I recorded this. Phone conversation, record spinning, and an excellent vibe.

Chill, lofi. Lo-fi, hip-hop, chill

tracks.title: Heaven in an Empty Train Station
tracks.summary: A newscast echoes through the corridors as some lonely busker plays from his soul, not caring if anyone is there to listen.

tracks.title: Monster Trucks
tracks.summary: As kids, my brother and I would play in the yard at night, hiding from the headlights of cars passing by, because if they saw us they would eat us alive!

tracks.title: Even the Tired Get Young
tracks.summary: At first you’re not sure what you’re getting into. It’s a circus! Playful and fun, but something’s slightly wrong, and weirdly disturbing.

tracks.title: Do What You Will
tracks.summary: laying on your back on a clear night, staring into the infinite space between the stars, admiring the grand design.

tracks.title: Church of the Universe
tracks.summary:
A funky dance vibe resounds through echoing, expansive synths and a tripped out jam.

On this album,“Church of the Universe” is the exception on to my track-a-day stint. It came a few months later, after I had traveled much, and then come home and bought my first computer based recording system. It kinda fits in, despite it’s vastly different recording method. I guess this song somehow represents the landing after the leap, the shore that welcomed me home after a wild, tumultuous journey.

feeds.title: Hiddenkind
feeds.description:
Dive into this lush world of musical experimentation, where real instruments mix with electronic ones, where beauty and fear struggle for dominance, where nature and song breathe warm life into the cold climate of synthetic sounds.
The concept for this album starts with the idea of a tribe in the isolated jungle, hidden away from civilization, practicing the old, beautiful ways of survival.
From there it may take you many places.
Enjoy

tracks.title: Control
tracks.summary:
Like it or not this is the deal
Reap what you sew, keep what you steal
and nobody here can stand to be near me
when they think I'm falling
So let me be clear when I go I'm not crawling

A moment of truth stuck in the wire
It's hard to ignore the only fire
So throw it away, give up for the day
and let you heart be shaken
yeah I can be broken, too, if you'd be patient

So say what you think won't make me stay
Like I thought this was okay
I just revel in decay

Nobody here knows why you'd show
If you love me you control me that's all you had to know.

A moment of truth stuck in the wires
It's hard to ignore the only fire
And nobody here can stand to be near me when they
Think I'm drinking
So let me be clear this ship is not done sinking
Not done sinking

Say what you want to darling, it don't mean nothing to me
Ambivalence sure seems charming but ain't what it used to be.

"Giving Up The Ghost" has been in the works since late 2021 - evolving, shifting, and transforming in almost every way. Please enjoy, and as always, thanks for your support.

feeds.title: Closer to Somewhere
feeds.description:
The Retrograde's second single "Closer to Somewhere" off their debut album "That's The Spirit!" under Cannabis Records. This song is about the struggle that we all sometimes feel in our lives. That feeling of being down on your luck, trying your hardest, but getting closer to nowhere. But all hope is not lost! We are so close... I can feel it, we can work it out... closer to somewhere!
(P)(C) Cannabis Records
Presented by Cannabis Records and Hash Power Music

The Retrograde's second single "Closer to Somewhere" off their debut album "That's The Spirit!" under Cannabis Records. This song is about the struggle that we all sometimes feel in our lives. That feeling of being down on your luck, trying your hardest, but getting closer to nowhere. But all hope is not lost! We are so close... I can feel it, we can work it out... closer to somewhere!
(P)(C) Cannabis Records

feeds.description: Tony Salomone is a songwriter and producer based out of Nashville, TN.  Originally from Columbus, OH, Tony employs a classic style of songwriting woven into an eclectic blend of energetic Alt Rock and heartfelt piano-driven Soul, reminiscent of Arctic Monkeys, The Black Keys and Royal Blood with echoes of Queen and The Beatles.  "Red Light" is written by Anthony Daniel Salomone & Daniel Christopher Salomone.

feeds.title: Gossip Queen
feeds.description: Zhaklina, originally from New York and of Albanian, Irish and Greek descent, is an Independent, Alternative Pop artist based in Nashville.  In 2019, Zhaklina began releasing a series of EP’s called “17 Reasons Why” dedicated to mental health awareness. With “Gossip Queen” being her most popular song yet and “Tattooed Roses” not too far behind, she is developing a space for her audience to feel seen.

feeds.description:
A bunch of best friends who grew up in the Buffalo, NY area making music throughout our childhood and teenage years. From left to right: Eddy, TJ, Kim, Bethany, Miles, Ethan. These songs were written by us from approximately 2003 to 2005. Think of this album as audio lore for early Doerfel/Fonda-verse music! 
Miles fronted much of the songwriting and arrangements of these songs, and I(TJ) felt this would be a fun album to release in Miles' honor. While I love ALL these songs, "Ode to Ashley" really captured the joy Miles and I had making music together. Thanks Ashley!

album.title: 18 Sundays
album.description:
A bunch of best friends who grew up in the Buffalo, NY area making music throughout our childhood and teenage years. From left to right: Eddy, TJ, Kim, Bethany, Miles, Ethan. These songs were written by us from approximately 2003 to 2005. Think of this album as audio lore for early Doerfel/Fonda-verse music! 

Miles fronted much of the songwriting and arrangements of these songs, and I(TJ) felt this would be a fun album to release in Miles' honor. While I love ALL these songs, "Ode to Ashley" really captured the joy Miles and I had making music together. Thanks Ashley!

We didn't have autotune back then, but there is something beautiful about the rawness of these tracks. Until we get to jam again in heaven, we love and miss you Miles, and may your music live on forever!
------------
Miles Fonda(4/15/88 to 1/21/23) - Drums, lead vocals.
Bethany Fonda - Lead and backing vocals.
Kim Doerfel - Lead and backing vocals, fiddle.
TJ Doerfel - Guitars.
Eddy Doerfel - Bass and mandolin.
Ethan Fonda - percussion and band jester.

To see what everyone is up to now check out https://www.doerfelverse.com and https://www.bethanyfonda.com/

Miles' splits go to his son Kaden.
Special thanks to our parents(Ralph and Tamala Fonda, Tom and Cheryl Doerfel) for helping us on our musical journey.

album.title: Into the Blue
album.description: by Robert Willey (2007).

tracks.title: May I ?
tracks.summary: The change heard on Into the Blue from Out of the Blue is due to a natural maturity over the years and advances in technology. Only the Yamaha KX76 controller and acoustic guitar remain, now in proximity to an iMac running Pro Tools LE and Reason, and a lone piece of outboard gear–an antique Digitech Vocalist harmonizer. Most of the synthesis and processing were done “in the box”. The improvement in sound quality was as inspiring as the excitement experienced with earlier setups. The sounds have gotten clearer, and the forms more linear, with smoother transitions between sections. An abundance of audio tracks and types of processing are available, along with new editing options. The whole process is sped up, which is good, because I have less time to compose now.“May I ?” was done with Reason. I never figured out exactly what was causing the weird plucking sound, or how to control its volume, but appreciate its serendipitous contribution.

tracks.title: for the Time Being
tracks.summary: “for the Time Being” is dedicated to the giver of the moments we have to explore life. The metallic balls of János Négyesy’s clock heard at the beginning and end of the song were recorded by Josef Kucera for one of our projects at U.C. San Diego sometime in the 1980’s.

tracks.title: Upstate
tracks.summary: “Upstate” was written while living in Oneonta, New York, after a visit to Brazil. I’m working on a book on Brazilian piano styles with Alfredo Cardim, who reminds me that samba should be played in cut time, with the bass player imitating the surdo part, with the first beat a bit muffled and the second beat louder. I gave in to the impulse to add sixteenth notes to the bass part on the bridge.

tracks.title: Into the Blue
tracks.summary: The impetus for changing the name from the original “Little Fox” to “Into the Blue” came from realizing its similarity with an earlier composition, “Out of the Blue.” I suppose the impulse for the chord progression comes from Pachebel’s “Canon in D”.

tracks.title: Diary of the Night
tracks.summary: “Diary of the Night” is a translation of the name of a restaurant in Belo Horizonte, Brazil.[ score ]

tracks.title: Where Did They Go?
tracks.summary: “Where Did They Go ?” is dedicated to my parents, George and Jill Willey.

feeds.title: Disciples by Design
feeds.description:
Straight out of Hamilton, Ontario, Canadian metallers Prismind are bringing an old school British heavy metal style combined with progressive details in their new album Disciples By Design.  The album starts off fast and smooth, keeping a steady pace throughout the track list so that you don’t miss a single headbangable moment.
    
    Prismind are:
    
    Kelly Kereliuk - Guitars
    John Mamone - Vocals
    Justin Faragher - Bass
    Mike Harshaw - Drums
    
    https://www.facebook.com/prismindband/

feeds.title: Push
feeds.description: "Push," the latest offering from The Synthesatsers, is a sonic odyssey that melds the pulsing beats of classic synth-pop with the expansive textures of modern electronic music. Released to critical acclaim, this album marks a bold step forward for the band, fusing their nostalgic undertones with a fresh, experimental edge. The Synthesatsers collaborated with renowned producer E.V. Synth, known for his work with pioneering electronic acts, to shape the sound of "Push." The production is meticulous, with a clarity that allows the interplay of synthesizers to shine through. Each track is arranged to take the listener on a journey...

album.title: Push
album.description: "Push," the latest offering from The Synthesatsers, is a sonic odyssey that melds the pulsing beats of classic synth-pop with the expansive textures of modern electronic music. Released to critical acclaim, this album marks a bold step forward for the band, fusing their nostalgic undertones with a fresh, experimental edge. The Synthesatsers collaborated with renowned producer E.V. Synth, known for his work with pioneering electronic acts, to shape the sound of "Push." The production is meticulous, with a clarity that allows the interplay of synthesizers to shine through. Each track is arranged to take the listener on a journey, with builds and drops that are both surprising and satisfying.

tracks.title: Cruising
tracks.subtitle: Cruising
tracks.summary: The song quickly introduces a steady, driving beat that mirrors the steady motion of a car in motion. The bass line is deep and moving, providing a solid foundation on which layers of synthesizers dance and weave. Textures ebb and flow like the passing scenery of a nocturnal journey, with a melodic lead synth that sings a haunting yet hopeful tune.

tracks.title: Happy Gnomes
tracks.subtitle: Happy Gnomes
tracks.summary: "Happy Gnomes" is The Synthesatsers' delightful detour into a more playful and quirky side of electronic music. The track begins with twinkling synths and a melody that bounces along with the joyous innocence of a children's tune. It’s easy to imagine the song serving as a soundtrack to a mythical world, full of wonder and miniaturized adventure. The song structure is buoyant, featuring a jaunty rhythm that skips and hops like the fantastical creatures it's named after. There's a prominent use of bell-like synth tones that mimic the sound of a xylophone, adding to the enchanting, fanciful vibe. A bouncy bassline underpins the melody, giving the song a danceable groove despite its lighthearted, almost mischievous melody.

tracks.title: Cataracts
tracks.subtitle: Cataracts
tracks.summary: "Cataracts" marks a dramatic turn within The Synthesatsers' repertoire, offering listeners a visceral, disturbing experience. The song starts with an unsettling drone that sets a tone of unease, followed by dissonant synth layers that weave in and out like a dense fog distorting reality. The composition of "Cataracts" features a slow-burning build-up, where arrhythmic beats create a sense of disorientation akin to the visual impairment the title suggests. The synths are grainy and abrasive, occasionally punctuated by what sounds like muffled, distorted voices or mechanical groans that add to the eerie atmosphere.

tracks.title: Let's Go
tracks.subtitle: Let's Go
tracks.summary: "Let's Go" is a burst of pure sonic energy, with The Synthesatsers channeling the electrifying spirit of synth-driven dance music. The track kicks off with an infectious beat and an upbeat tempo, setting the scene for a fun and dynamic listening experience. This track revolves around a central, pulsating synth riff that serves as the backbone of the song. Layered on top are intricate, fast-paced melodies and bright, shimmering chords that build up to a rousing drop. The rhythm section is tight and punchy, with drum machines providing a crisp foundation for the driving basslines.

tracks.title: Coconuts and Catnip
tracks.subtitle: Coconuts and Catnip
tracks.summary: This track is a joyful concoction, a left-field piece that fuses electronic exuberance with organic sounds. It begins with the tropical tones of steel drums or a marimba, layered over synthetic grooves that bring to mind the image of cats playfully frolicking in a sun-drenched locale. "Coconuts and Catnip" weaves a playful melody with a laid-back yet infectious rhythm. It features a blend of traditional electronic elements with unexpected instruments and sounds, like the rustling of leaves, the shake of a maraca, or the quirky twang of a ukulele, creating a sonic palette that's both beachy and digital.

feeds.description:
Beyond the Hills is a song that arrived while hiking the beautiful Pennsylvania hills and mountainsides. 
Anni wrote the piano and asked her nursing buddy and musician friend, Yovianna Garcia Alvarado, to collaborate. Yovi wrote a classical guitar addition that sings the melody of this instrumental piece.

feeds.description:

Bass, Gerald Kebreau; Drums, Jason Kent
Recorded in 2014 as part of the self titled "Unclazzified" EP

tracks.title: Bend
tracks.summary: (Linear notes from the album) Recorded at Hollywood Sound Recorders in Hollywood, CA and The Farm Recording Studios in North Hollywood. Mixed at Hollywood Sound Recorders. Mastered by Mark Chalecki at Tower Mastering. Cover art by Jeffrey Damm. All songs written and arranged by Jim Costello, except "Isabelle," written by Jim Costello and Scott Appleton. Copyright 1996, Nomadic Slacker Publishing. Musicians: Rob Ahlers - Drums. Kristin Endsley - Backing Vocals. Jim Ervin - organ on "Bend". Michael Faue - Percussion. Kate Gibson - vocals on "Isabelle." Tim Godwin - too many electric and slide parts to remember. Lily Hadyn - violin. Todd Hodulik - guitar solo on "Center". Chris Johnson - bass on "Center," "Bend" and "Tell Me I Have More". The David Kainsley Trio - trumpets on "Bend". Karen Marks - Saxophones. Novi Novog - Viola. Tom Sullivan Jr. - Bass on "Again," "This," and "Love Me Like Before". Geri Sutyak - Cello. Jim Costello - Vocals, acoustic guitar, bass on "See Me There".

tracks.title: They Don't Know
tracks.summary:
We picked this song to release on Episode 4 of our podcast, "Into The Doerfel-verse" If you find any value in this song, please let us know!

Notice the instruments in the song art. Our friend Jim Stoneman made us hockey sticks guitars which we would play a few songs on every show. All us Doerfel boys wanted to play hockey when we grew up, instead we turned into wimpy musicians! We still enjoy hitting the ice from time to time.
